    {
        "content": "<p>This thread is for discussing this paper:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>John Baez, Joe Moeller and Owen Lynch, <a href=\"http://math.ucr.edu/home/baez/thermostatics.pdf\">Compositional thermostatics</a>.</li>\n</ul>\n<blockquote>\n<p><strong>Abstract.</strong> We define a thermostatic system to be a convex space of states together with a concave function sending each state to its entropy, which is an extended real number. This definition applies to classical thermodynamics, classical statistical mechanics, quantum statistical mechanics, and also generalized probabilistic theories of the sort studied in quantum foundations. It also allows us to treat a heat bath as a thermostatic system on an equal footing with any other. We construct an operad whose operations are convex relations from a product of convex spaces to a single convex space, and prove that thermostatic systems are algebras of this operad. This gives a general, rigorous formalism for combining thermostatic systems, which captures the fact that such systems maximize entropy subject to whatever constraints are imposed upon them.</p>\n</blockquote>",
        "id": 262020091,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1637288915
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I blogged about this paper:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>John Baez, <a href=\"https://johncarlosbaez.wordpress.com/2021/11/22/compositional-thermostatics/\">Compositional thermostatics</a>, <em>Azimuth</em>.</li>\n</ul>",
        "id": 262339354,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1637597154
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So did <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"280755\">@Owen Lynch</span>:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Owen Lynch, <a href=\"https://topos.site/blog/2021/09/compositional-thermostatics/\">Compositional thermostatics</a>, <em>Topos Institute Blog</em>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>Mine gets more into the definition of \"convex space\" and \"thermostatic system\", while his goes further in developing the motivations from physics, and how we use our setup to actually compose thermostatic systems.</p>",
        "id": 262339589,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1637597231
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On Twitter someone reading about our paper recommended this book:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>Jan Brinkhuis, <em><a href=\"https://link.springer.com/book/10.1007/978-3-030-41804-5\">Convex Analysis for Optimization</a></em>.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>He said there's projective geometry lurking around here.  I don't know how.   Guess I'll have to look at the book!</p>",
        "id": 262515169,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1637702425
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I have thought before that extensive coordinates are kind of projective, because scaling all of them uniformly does not change the behavior of the system.</p>",
        "id": 262515410,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637702562
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Maybe that's what is hinted at.   There's also a connection between contact geometry and projective geometry.  But until I look at the book, these are just guesses!</p>",
        "id": 262521450,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1637705677
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I've started to read the book, and so far it's living up to its subtitle of \"A Unified Approach\"</p>",
        "id": 262524416,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637707249
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Good?</p>",
        "id": 262536135,
        "sender_full_name": "John Baez",
        "timestamp": 1637716552
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yeah, it's tying together some things that have been confusing me</p>",
        "id": 262538148,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637718679
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Their \"unified method\" is to translate to convex cones. Which reminds me a lot of using unnormalized probability distributions....</p>",
        "id": 262602486,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637767526
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They give a different definition of a dual of a convex set, which requires the convex set to be embedded in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{R}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>. Namely, the dual of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>C</mi><mo>⊆</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi>n</mi></msup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">C \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}^n</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8193em;vertical-align:-0.136em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> consists of all linear functionals <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><msup><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mi>n</mi></msup><mo>→</mo><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi \\colon \\mathbb{R}^n \\to \\mathbb{R}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.8889em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.6644em;\"><span style=\"top:-3.063em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathnormal mtight\">n</span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span></span></span></span> such that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>ϕ</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">(</mo><mi>C</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">)</mo><mo>⊆</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">R</mi><mrow><mo>≥</mo><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\phi(C) \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}_{\\geq 0}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">ϕ</span><span class=\"mopen\">(</span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07153em;\">C</span><span class=\"mclose\">)</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">⊆</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9341em;vertical-align:-0.2452em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathbb\">R</span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.3011em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.55em;margin-left:0em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mrel mtight\">≥</span><span class=\"mord mtight\">0</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2452em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.</p>",
        "id": 262605808,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637769133
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>With this definition, the double-dual is in fact the original space.</p>",
        "id": 262605896,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637769171
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Even though the dual is not generally the \"same dimension\" as the original space.</p>",
        "id": 262606003,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637769221
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A convex function is a function whose epigraph is convex, where the epigraph is all of the points lying above the graph of the function.</p>\n<p>The necessity of functions taking values in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo stretchy=\"false\">[</mo><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo separator=\"true\">,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi><mo stretchy=\"false\">]</mo></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">[-\\infty,\\infty]</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1em;vertical-align:-0.25em;\"></span><span class=\"mopen\">[</span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mpunct\">,</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span><span class=\"mclose\">]</span></span></span></span> is also because we want to allow empty and unbounded epigraphs. I.e. the constant function at <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.4306em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span> has an empty epigraph, and a function that takes values of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">∞</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">-\\infty</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">−</span><span class=\"mord\">∞</span></span></span></span> has an epigraph that contains arbitrarily low points.</p>",
        "id": 262607698,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637769983
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>They figure out how to define all of the common binary operations on convex sets (minkowski sum, intersection, convex hull of the union, and inverse sum) using translation to convex cones and the operations of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi>X</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+ \\colon X \\times X \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta \\colon X \\to X \\times X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. I feel like this ought to be able to be categorified using frobenius monoids.</p>",
        "id": 262608031,
        "sender_full_name": "Owen Lynch",
        "timestamp": 1637770156
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"280755\">Owen Lynch</span> <a href=\"#narrow/stream/306433-practice.3A-thermodynamics/topic/compositional.20thermostatics/near/262608031\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>They figure out how to define all of the common binary operations on convex sets (minkowski sum, intersection, convex hull of the union, and inverse sum) using translation to convex cones and the operations of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mo>+</mo><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi>X</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">+ \\colon X \\times X \\to X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">+</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span> and <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Δ</mi><mspace></mspace><mspace width=\"0.1111em\"/><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0.17em\"></mo><mtext> ⁣</mtext><mo lspace=\"0em\" rspace=\"0em\">:</mo><mspace width=\"0.3333em\"/><mi>X</mi><mo>→</mo><mi>X</mi><mo>×</mo><mi>X</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\Delta \\colon X \\to X \\times X</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\">Δ</span><span class=\"mspace nobreak\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1111em;\"></span><span class=\"mpunct\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:-0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.1667em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mrel\">:</span></span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.3333em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span><span class=\"mrel\">→</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2778em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.7667em;vertical-align:-0.0833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span><span class=\"mbin\">×</span><span class=\"mspace\" style=\"margin-right:0.2222em;\"></span></span><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6833em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\" style=\"margin-right:0.07847em;\">X</span></span></span></span>. I feel like this ought to be able to be categorified using frobenius monoids.</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>It has! <a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2105.10946\">https://arxiv.org/abs/2105.10946</a></p>",
        "id": 262609063,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Piedeleu",
        "timestamp": 1637770624
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Amazing!</p>",
